meta.description:
Label Generation Rules for the Root Zone — LGR-4

Note: this merged file is intended to be used for testing a label for conflicts with existing labels irrespective of their script. However, it can neither be used to conclusively establish the validity of any label in the context of a specific script nor to generate the set of allocatable variant labels for that label (see Section 5.2, "Common LGR" in [RZ-LGR-4-Overview]).

Overview

This document, together with the set of element LGRs, specifies an integrated collection of Label Generation Rules for the Root Zone. For more details on the Root Zone LGRs and their development see "Root Zone Label Generation Rules - LGR-4: Overview and Summary" [RZ-LGR-4-Overview]. This file is one of a set of LGR files that together form an integrated LGR for the DNS Root Zone [RZ-LGR-4]. The format of this file follows [RFC 7940].

Element LGRs

The Label Generation Rules for the Root Zone (LGR-4) are integrated from the following set of script-specific element LGRs:

  • Root Zone Label Generation Rules for the Arabic Script (und-Arab) [101]
  • Root Zone Label Generation Rules for the Bengali Script (und-Beng) [102]
  • Root Zone Label Generation Rules for the Chinese Script (und-Hani) [103]
  • Root Zone Label Generation Rules for the Devanagari Script (und-Deva) [104]
  • Root Zone Label Generation Rules for the Ethiopic Script (und-Ethi) [105]
  • Root Zone Label Generation Rules for the Georgian Script (und-Geor) [106]
  • Root Zone Label Generation Rules for the Gujarati Script (und-Gujr) [107]
  • Root Zone Label Generation Rules for the Gurmukhi Script (und-Guru) [108]
  • Root Zone Label Generation Rules for the Hebrew Script (und-Hebr) [109]
  • Root Zone Label Generation Rules for the Kannada Script (und-Knda) [110]
  • Root Zone Label Generation Rules for the Khmer Script (und-Khmr) [111]
  • Root Zone Label Generation Rules for the Lao Script (und-Laoo) [112]
  • Root Zone Label Generation Rules for the Malayalam Script (und-Mlym) [113]
  • Root Zone Label Generation Rules for the Oriya Script (und-Orya) [114]
  • Root Zone Label Generation Rules for the Sinhala Script (und-Sinh) [115]
  • Root Zone Label Generation Rules for the Tamil Script (und-Taml) [116]
  • Root Zone Label Generation Rules for the Telugu Script (und-Telu) [117]
  • Root Zone Label Generation Rules for the Thai Script (und-Thai) [118]

Each element LGR provides the complete specification for determining both the validity of a label in the given script, as well as the set of allocatableblocked labels may contain mixed script or cross-script labels, it cannot be computed from the element LGR. See Section 5.2, "Steps in Processing a Label" in [RZ-LGR-4-Overview].

Each LGR represents in full the underlying, proposal for the script-based LGR, except for changes required by the integration process or for uniformity of presentation. See Section 3, "Integration and Contents of LGR-4" in [RZ-LGR-4-Overview].

Merged LGR

This merged, or common, LGR has been machine generated by combining the data from all element LGRs plus a common preamble containing this description and the list of references used in this merged LGR. The merged LGR contains the union of the repertoire, variant mappings and Whole Label Evaluation (WLE) rules of the element LGRs as described in the following sections. Data that are necessarily script-dependent, such as the type for variant mappings have been removed or replaced by default values, such as "blocked".

When processing an applied for label, this merged LGR presents the complete data and specification needed for conflict checking with any existing label, independent of script. This is in contrast to the script-specific element LGRs, each of which presents the complete data and specification to determine the validity and full set of allocatable variants for the label, when applied for under that script. See also Section 5, "Using the LGR" in [RZ-LGR-4-Overview]. In particular, the merged LGR contains a complete set of all cross-script and cross-repertoire variants defined for the Root Zone.

Repertoire

The repertoire of the integrated Root Zone LGR is the cumulative repertoire of all the element LGRs that have been integrated into this version. Those repertoires, in turn were developed based on [MSR-4], which is a subset of [Unicode 6.3].

As a Root Zone LGR, the repertoire includes neither digits nor the HYPHEN-MINUS.

For further details, see Section 3.2.1, "Repertoire" in [RZ-LGR-4-Overview].

Each code point or range is tagged with the script or scripts that the code point is used with, and a reference to the Unicode Standard in which the code point was first encoded; see "References" below. Some code points are also tagged with script-specific classifications. These tags have been prefixed with the Unicode script identifier in the merged LGR.

Variants

The variant mappings in this LGR are the union of the non-reflexive variant mappings from all the element LGRs that have been integrated into this version of the Root Zone LGR. Because the disposition of variant labels, for example as "allocatable", is specific to each script, information related to that cannot be expressed in the script-neutral context of this merged file. Instead, all merged variant mappings are labeled as "blocked" in this document as needed for conflict checking. See also Section 3.2.2, "Variants" in [RZ-LGR-4-Overview].

As the repertoires are merged, any code point with a reflexive "out-of-repertoire-var" mapping in all element LGRs containing that code point will be considered not part of the merged repertoire and removed. If, however, any element LGR contains that code point as part of its repertoire, only the reflexive "out-of-repertoire-var" mapping will be removed. In contrast, in the Element LGRs, all code points and mappings defined are always retained, independent of whether they are part of the merged repertoire.

Implicit Coss-script Variants: Not all element LGRs explicitly specify all variants to other scripts and repertoires, choosing instead to inherit those defined in other script LGRs implicitly. Nevertheless, as long as cross-script variants are defined in at least one LGR, they will be part of this merged LGR and are considered in effect for all LGRs that contain the relevant code points. However, in all cases, each element LGR always lists all of the applicable in-script variants. This is another reason why the merged LGR must be used to determine conflicts (two labels blocking each other) while the element LGRs are used to determine the set of allocatable labels under that LGR.

Context Rules for Variants: some of the variants defined in this LGR are "effective null variants", that is, some code points in the source map to "nothing" in the target with all other code points unchanged. (Because mappings are symmetric, it does not matter whether it is the forward or reverse mapping that maps to "null"). Such variants require a context rule to keep the variant set well behaved. Symmetry requires the same context rule for both forward and reverse mappings.

In other cases, the sequences or code points making up source and target are constrained by explicit context rules on the code points (or by implicit context rules defined for the adjacent code points). In such a case, any variants may require context rules that match the intersection between the effective contexts for both source and target; otherwise, a sequence might be considered valid in some variant label when it would not be valid in an equivalent context in an original label. See Section 6.4.2 in [RZ-LGR-4-Overview].

Overlapping Variants:Some sequences may overlap, that is, they share a common part with another sequence or code point, so that, in partitioning a label into code points and sequences, more than one partition is possible. In these cases, variants have to be computed for all possible partitions. In some cases, context rules on sequences or variants are defined to curtail any unwanted side effects of such multiple partitioning, such as having each partition being part of a different variant label set, or generating a different index variant. For further discussion, see Section 6 in [RZ-LGR-4-Overview].

The specification of variants in the Root Zone LGR follows the guidelines in [RFC 8228].

Character Classes

This merged LGR includes the cumulative set of character classes from all the element LGRs that have been integrated into this version of the Root Zone LGR. See Section 3.2.3, "Character Classes" in [RZ-LGR-4-Overview]. The names for any script-specific character classes have been prefixed with the Unicode script identifier.

Whole Label Evaluation (WLE) and Context Rules

This merged LGR includes the cumulative set of WLE and context rules and actions from all the element LGRs that have been integrated into this version of the Root Zone LGR. See Section 3.2.4, "Whole Label Evaluation Rules (WLE)" [RZ-LGR-4-Overview]. See also the comments given for each rule or action.

Default Whole Label Evaluation Rules and Actions

The integrated LGR includes the set of required default WLE rules and actions applicable to the Root Zone and defined in [MSR-4]. They are marked with ⍟. These default rules include the restrictions defined in [RFC 5891] on placement of combining marks.

Script-specific WLE rules

The names for any script-specific rules have been prefixed with the Unicode script identifier.

Script-specific Actions

Some actions are triggered by script-specific variant type values. While such actions are collected here for reference, they are inoperative in the context of the merged LGR because in the merged LGR all variant type values have been mapped to "blocked".

Methodology and Contributors

The Root Zone Label Generation Rules - LGR-4 were integrated by the Integration Panel [IP] from a set of proposals for script-based root zone LGRs developed by community-based Generation Panels [GPs] in an open process with multiple public consultations defined in [Procedure] and [Guidelines]. For more information on the methodology and contributors, see [RZ-LGR-4-Overview], in particular Section 2, "Process of Integration" and Section 8, "Contributors".

Integration Panel

According to the "Procedure to Develop and Maintain the Label Generation Rules for the Root Zone in Respect of IDNA Labels" [Procedure], the Integration Panel is tasked with reviewing each script LGR proposal for the Root Zone and delivering an integrated Root Zone LGR after accepting them. Its members consist of experts in the area of Unicode, Linguistics and Writing Systems, Domain Name System (DNS) and IDNA. The Integration Panel was constituted on September 6, 2013 with the following members:

  • Marc Blanchet
  • Asmus Freytag
  • Michel Suignard
  • Nicholas Ostler
  • Wil Tan

References

In the listing of the repertoire, references starting at [0] refer to Unicode Standard versions in which the corresponding code points were initially encoded. References [101] and above correspond to the script-specific LGRs that include the repertoire item. Repertoire items may have more than one reference.

var.comment: U+0622 ALEF WITH MADDA ABOVE is simplified to U+0627 ALEF in the Arabic language
U+0623 ALEF WITH HAMZA ABOVE is simplified to U+0627 ALEF in the Arabic language
U+0624 WAV WITH HAMZA ABOVE is simplified to U+0648 WAV in the Arabic language
U+0625 ALEF WITH HAMZA BELOW is simplified to U+0627 ALEF in the Arabic language
In the Arabic language, U+0647 HEH may be substituted for U+0629 TEH MARBUTA. [RFC 6365]

The two are visually identical and the same label could be typed using one or the other based on the set language settings and keyboard layout of a user. Labels in the Arabic language using U+0629 TEH MARBUTA in the final and isolated positions will be typed in other languages using U+06C3 TEH MARBUTA GOAL (Urdu, etc.) which is identical in isolated and has a variant glyph or identical glyph form in final position
Used interchangeably in Africa for languages using Western (African) orthography
Used interchangeably in Africa for languages using Western (African) orthography
The two have identical shapes in initial and medial positions and are used by different language communities to refer to the same letter
The two have similar (interchangeable) shapes in initial and medial positions and are used by different language communities to refer to the same letter
Used interchangeably in Africa for languages using Western (African) orthography

Labels in the Arabic language using U+0647 HEH in the final and isolated positions will be typed in other languages using U+06C1 HEH GOAL (Urdu, Pashto, Saraiki, etc.) which is identical in isolated and has a variant glyph or identical glyph form in final position
The two are visually identical and the same label could be typed using one or the other based on the set language settings and keyboard layout of a user
U+0672 ALEF WITH WAVY HAMZA ABOVE is simplified to U+0627 ALEF in the Kashmiri language
The two have similar (interchangeable) shapes in initial and medial positions and are used by different language communities to refer to the same letter
U+06AB KAF WITH RING interchangeably used in Pashto with U+06AF GAF
Iraqi Arabic uses U+06AF GAF, whereas Moroccan Arabic uses U+0763 KEHEH WITH THREE DOTS ABOVE
U+06C0 HEH WITH YEH ABOVE is simplified to U+0647 HEH in some languages (Kurdish)

This is not allocatable in either direction because, unlike the allocatable relationship between U+0647 HEH and U+0629 TEH MARBUTA due to variation in the Arabic language, Urdu and other languages using U+06C1 HEH GOAL do not exhibit such variation with U+06C3 TEH MARBUTA GOAL
U+06C2 HEH GOAL WITH HAMZA ABOVE is simplified to U+06C1 HEH GOAL in Urdu

rule.name: Thai--follows-consonant-av-bv
rule.comment: WLE 7.7, 7.8: A tone-mark, THANTHAKHAT, NIKAHIT can only follow a consonant, above-vowel or below-vowel

action.comment: labels with leading combining marks are invalid ⍟
Section 7, WLE 6: Label does not begin with L
Section 7, WLE 10: Label cannot contain only RRA
WLE 10: U+09B0 and U+09F0 cannot be mixed.
any variant label with a code point out of repertoire is invalid ⍟
do not mix two representations of 'Shri' in the same label
any label with more than two subscript consonants in a row is invalid
do not mix Arabic letters KAF and KEHEH in the same label
do not mix Arabic letters KAF and SWASH KAF in the same label
do not mix Arabic letters ALEF MAKSURA and FARSI YEH in the same label
do not mix Arabic letters HEH and HEH GOAL in the same label
do not mix Arabic letters HEH GOAL and AE in the same label
do not mix Arabic letters HEH and AE in the same label
do not mix Arabic letters HEH and HEH DOACHASHMEE in the same label
do not mix Arabic letters TEH MARBUTA and FEH WITH DOT MOVED BELOW in the same label
do not mix Arabic letters NOON WITH THREE DOTS ABOVE and YEH WITH THREE DOTS BELOW in the same label
do not mix Arabic letters PEH and NOON WITH THREE DOTS ABOVE in the same label
do not mix Arabic letters FEH and FEH WITH DOT MOVED BELOW in the same label
do not mix Arabic letters QAF and QAF WITH DOT ABOVE in the same label
do not mix Arabic letters FEH and QAF WITH DOT ABOVE in the same label
do not mix Arabic letters KAF WITH RING and GAF in the same label
do not mix Arabic letters KAF WITH RING and KEHEH WITH THREE DOTS ABOVE
do not mix Arabic letters GAF and KEHEH WITH THREE DOTS ABOVE in the same label
any variant label containing blocked variants is blocked ⍟
variant labels with all variants allocatable are allocatable ⍟
any label of simplified type 1 is allocatable
any label of simplified type 2 is allocatable
any label of traditional type 1 is allocatable
any label of traditional type 2 is allocatable

action.any-variant: simp trad both simp-1 simp-2 trad-1 trad-2
action.comment: any other mixed labels are blocked
original label is allocatable
catch all (default action) ⍟ | catch all; default action ⍟
